<BlogPost
  title="2017 KTM 300xc vs 2017 Husqvarna tx300"
  description=""
  category="Uncategorized"
  categorySlug="uncategorized"
>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-2700" src="https://www.oregonmotorcyclerental.com/newsite/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-ktm-300-300x170.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="170" srcset="../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-ktm-300-300x170.jpg 300w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-ktm-300-768x436.jpg 768w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-ktm-300-257x146.jpg 257w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-ktm-300-50x28.jpg 50w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-ktm-300-132x75.jpg 132w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-ktm-300.jpg 780w" sizes="(max-width:767px) 300px, 300px" /> <img decoding="async" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-2701" src="https://www.oregonmotorcyclerental.com/newsite/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-husky-300-300x170.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="170" srcset="../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-husky-300-300x170.jpg 300w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-husky-300-768x436.jpg 768w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-husky-300-1024x581.jpg 1024w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-husky-300-257x146.jpg 257w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-husky-300-50x28.jpg 50w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-husky-300-132x75.jpg 132w, ../../wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2017-husky-300.jpg 1600w" sizes="(max-width:767px) 300px, 300px" />Now, we have some serious hours on the 17&#8217;s and the feedback is quite interesting. My mechanic thinks the same parts make the same bike, that tuning is the difference in ride quality. I beg to differ. I have 4 300&#8217;s, 2 xc and 2 White Huskies, 2 with high compression heads, 2 stock heads. The KTM used a 45,000th cylinder shave, and was quite ballistic. It will climb the impossible, and pull you in 3rd gear I might add. It&#8217;s a handfull in tight terrain and requires a practiced throttle hand at all times, or you will overshoot your target. The suspension runs stock spring on the AER fork at 135 lbs pressure, 7 clicks in on the right leg. The shock runs a 48 spring 10 clicks in on rebound and 10 in on compression. I&#8217;ve tried several variations, and this seems to be my sweetspot for my 200lbs with the KTM. The ride is stiff, to say the least, well stiff compared to the 2 Huskies, but this is where the KTM liked to run. Less air, meant harsh ride, 150 hours of run time, same effect.</p>
<p>The Husky, cylinder head is shaved to 42,000ths. The bike is super strong,  just a tad more controllable. That gentle pull of the stock head, is replaced by a firm but not overwhelming power. Perfect in my book. Suspension; I used to wonder why KTM puts Jarvis on the Husqvarna, I mean, he&#8217;s the best, right? Why wouldn&#8217;t you have him competing on the flagship machine? Well, I think Graham chose his steed based on the ride qualities he likes. With me, I&#8217;m 15% faster on the Huskie. The plush feel of the ride is very apparent to me and all the riders I put on them. Silky smooth and soft is the feel. Settings: I have been running the Husky with 120 to 125 lbs in the fork 10 clicks in. The shock runs the same 48 spring, and 10 clicks in just like the KTM. The bike just carries the softer pressure beautifully. No bottoming, soaks up everything. Quite a dramatic difference between the two. So, I will chock up all this rhetoric now. I think it all comes down to the sub-frame. The composite is just flexy enough to make things plush. What genius came up with this idea? We may never know just who was responsible, but that boy deserves a raise in my book. What about Jetting you ask? That is a little insider info and will remain off the record. I will say the Mikuni is super tough to get right, and needs constant tweeking for elevation change.</p>
<p>Grab one before EFI. This generation of 300&#8217;s just might be he best KTM will ever produce. Cheers</p>
</BlogPost>
